AGRICULTURAL 
 ECONOMICS 
 Farming-based Money flow 38 (2008) 151-165 
 
 Measuring hits/effects and helpful changes to climate change: a (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) Ricardian 
 model of African animals management1 
 S. Niggol Seoa,a-- , Robert Mendelsohnb 
 b School 
 
 a World Bank, 8508 16th Street, Suite 302, Silver Spring, MD 20910, USA 
 of Forestry and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) Studies, 230 Prospect St., New Place, CT 06511, USA 
 
 Received 29 April 2007; received in changed form 15 August 2007; accepted 15 August 2007 
 
 Abstract 
 This article develops a new thin sliceal way(s) of doing things that clearly includes helpful change into an analysis of the hits/effects of climate change. 
 The way(s) of doing things examines how a farmer will change choices of species and number to change to fit climate. The approach is applied to study Africa, 
 where the hits/effects of climate change are expected to be the worst. The results point to/show that in warmer places, African farmers switch from 
 beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  to more heat-tolerant goats and sheep. In wetter places, farmers switch from (cows, bulls, etc.)  and sheep to goats and chickens. The results point to/show 
 that large commercial animals operations (focusing on doing one thing very well) in beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  will be hard hit from climate change whereas small farmers who can easily 
 substitute to goats and/or sheep will be more tough. 
 JEL classification: C53, O13, O18, O55, R11 
 Keywords: Climate change; Africa; Animals; Cross-sectional helpful change analysis 
 
 1. Introduction 
 This article uses thin sliceal (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) to explore how 
 farmers change to fit (coming from the outside of something) (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) factors such as climate and soils. The model builds on the original ideas of 
 the Ricardian model that explored the center  of land value 
 per hectare (Mendelsohn et al., 1994). Although the Ricardian 
 model (takes control of) helpful change in its measure of hits/effects, it does 
 not provide any understanding of how farmers change. In this article, we develop a new approach, a (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) Ricardian Model, 
 that clearly models the hidden (under) endogenous decisions by 
 farmers. By comparing choices of farmers who face different 
 conditions, the model uncovers how farmers change. (may or may not happen, depending on something) 
 incomes, using a Ricardian approach, are then guessed for 
 each choice made by each farmer. 
