 We develop this new method and then apply it to study how 
 African farmers change  animals management to climate. We 
 explore which species they choose, how many animals they 
 own, and how net money/money income per animal for each species changes. 
 Understanding helpful change is an important goal in itself to help 
 planning by policy makers and private people. However, 
 understanding helpful change is also important if one is interested 
 in numbering the hits/effects of climate change. Forecasts that 
 over- or underpredict helpful change will under- or overpredict the 
 leftover/extra damages from climate change. 
 Climate hit/effect studies have regularly (described the future) long/big 
 hits/effects to the farming-based part/area from climate change across 
 the globe (Pearce et al., 1996; McCarthy et al., 2001; Tol, 2002). 
 Most of farming-based studies on the effect of climate change 
 have focused on crops. However, a large fraction of farming-based 
 output is from animals. In the United States, animals account 
 for about 40% of the market value of farming-based products sold 
 (USDA, 2002). Almost 80% of African farming-based land is used 
 for grazing. Yet there are very few money-based analyses of (related to the Earth's weather) effects on animals. An important exception is the study 
 of the effects of climate change on American animals (Adams 
 et al., 1999). American animals appear not to be (able to be hurt) 
 to climate change because most live in protected (surrounding conditions) 
 (sheds, barns, etc.) and rely heavily on additional/helping feed (e.g., 
 hay and corn). African animals have no (serving or acting to prevent harm) structures 
 and they graze off the land. As a result, we expect that 
 
