 African animals will be sensitive to climate change. In a separate article, the Ricardian model is applied to African animals 
 data (Seo et al., 2007) and shows that animals are sensitive 
 to climate. In this article we provide understanding of how farmers 
 (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) to climate and what they might do in the future. 
 The hidden (under) explanation of the (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) Ricardian Model is 
 developed in the next section. Section 3 discusses how data 
 were collected from over 5,000 farmers who own animals in 
 10 countries across Africa for this study. Section 4 discusses 
 the guess procedure and the thin sliceal scientific results. Forecasted hits/effects from three climate change pictures/situations 
 created by Air-related Ocean-related General Circulation Models (AOGCMs) are then examined in Section 5. The article 
 ends with a summary of results and policy effects/results/suggestions. 
 2. Explanation 
 A farmer's optimization decision can be seen as a (happening together) multiple-stage procedure. The farmer chooses the levels 
 of inputs, the desired number of animals, and the species that 
 will produce the highest net (money made/good thing received). Given the profit-making the most of 
 inputs from each farmer, one can guess the centers of profitmaximizing choices for each species across (coming from the outside of something) (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) factors such as temperature or (rain, snow, etc.). These 
 are the individual centers that lie beneath the overall profit function 
 for the farm (Mendelsohn et al., 1994). We call the approach 
 a "cross-sectional helpful change model" because it guesses the 
 choice of a clearly stated/particular animal, the number of animals, and the hidden (under) profit response functions per animal for each species 
 
 that form the overall profit function. For example, in Fig. 1 
 we display a traditional Ricardian response function with respect to hardenature. Underneath the center  of all choices is a 
 set of species-clearly stated/particular response functions. Given the climate, 
 the farmer must choose the most money-making species and also the 
 inputs that will (make as big as possible) the value of that species. We examine 
 the individual net money/money income functions for each species as well as 
 the overall net money/money income function across all species. We assume 
 that each farmer makes his animal farming/managing money decisions to (make as big as possible) (money made/good thing received). 2 Because of this, the chance that a species is chosen 
 depends on the money-making ability of that animal species (or crop if 
 one wants to examine the crop part/area). We assume that farmer 
 i's (money made/good thing received) in choosing animals j (j = 1, 2, . . . , J) is 
 Ïj i = V (Zj i ) + Îµj i , 
 
