 The limits/guidelines can be guessed by the maximum chance method using an repeating/repetitive (not going in a straight line) optimization way of doing things such as the Newton-Raphson method. These guesses 
 are CAN (Consistent and Asymptotically (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)) under standard (happening over and over again in a predictable way) conditions (McFadden, 1999). 
 Note that farmers can choose more than one species of animals among the five species in our study. That is, there are many 
 combinations of animals species that the farmer could choose. 
 In this analysis, we assume that farmers choose one first (or most important) 
 species from the five species. A first (or most important) species is defined as 
 that which creates the highest total net money/money income for the farm 
 (Train, 2003). In another analysis of animals choice, we compare this approach using the first (or most important) species with an different 
 (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection) approach that examines all possible choices including 
 combinations of species (Seo and Mendelsohn, 2007). The two 
 approaches produce almost the same  results. 
 (may or may not happen, depending on something) on the animals species chosen, we guess the 
 best number of animals per farm for each species and the 
 net money/money income per animal for each species. We depend on a two-stage 
 model. In the first stage, we guess the chance of selecting 
 a species (Eq. 5). In the second stage, (may or may not happen, depending on something) on the choice 
 of a clearly stated/particular species, we guess the best number of that 
 species and the net money/money income per animal. We identify the species 
 choice equations using the relative prices of each choice. We 
 identify the number of animal equations using the percentage 
 of grassland in the district. Note that this more general (number or thing that changes) 
 was used instead of grassland on the farm because many African 
 animals owners graze animals on common lands. 
