 The change in welfare resulting from a nonmarginal change 
 in climate can be figured out/calculated as the difference in the expected 
 net money/money income in the two states before and after climate change. 
 Suppose that climate changes from Cbefore to Cafter . Then the 
 change in welfare can be came close to as 
 Wi = Wi (Cafter ) a' Wi (Cbefore ). 
 
 (13) 
 
 The doubt surrounding our measure of the welfare 
 change can be described by the 95% confidence period of time (or space) of 
 the expected climate change hit/effect. In way of thinking/basic truth/rule, there are two 
 ways to calculate confidence periods of time (or space): parametric and nonparametric. It is hard to calculate the variance of the climate 
 change hit/effect parametrically in this model because welfare is 
 the product of three (statements about the future). We provide doubt guesses in this study via a helping thing method by resampling 200 
 times from the original sample and calculating the 95% confidence period of time (or space) using the mean and the standard moving away of 
 the resulting climate change hits/effects (Andrews and Buchinsky, 
 2000). 
 3. Data 
 Data for this study come from a larger Worldwide  (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) Facility (GEF)-World Bank project to study climate change 
 hits/effects on farming in Africa (Dinar et al., 2008). The countries included were Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Egypt, Ethiopia, 
 Ghana, Kenya, Niger, Senegal, South Africa, and Zambia. (Zimbabwe had to be dropped from the animals analysis because 
 of mixed-up/disturbed conditions in that country during the survey.) The 
 
 countries were selected to represent the wide range of climate 
 throughout Africa. Districts within each country were selected 
 to provide as much within-country climate difference/different version as possible. 
 Because existing money-based data were not (good) enough to support 
 an analysis, an money-based survey of farmers was managed and did/done. The 
 original survey interviewed more than 9,000 farmers from 11 
 countries. Within that sample, more than 5,000 were animals 
 farmers (Kurukulasuriya et al., 2006). 
 The animals data include information on species, the stock 
 of animals owned, and the animals products and animals 
 sold during the period of July 2002 to June 2003 (the data 
 from Kenya, Ethiopia, and Cameroon cover the period July 
 2003 to June 2004). The data identify the five major types of 
 animals in Africa as beef (cows, bulls, etc.), dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), goats, sheep, 
 and chickens. Other less often recorded animals include 
 pigs, breeding bulls, oxen, camels, ducks, guinea bird, horses, 
 bees, and doves. The major animals products sold were milk, 
 meat, eggs, wool, and leather. Other products included butter, 
 cheese, honey, skins, and poop/fertilizer. The five major animals 
 accounted for 93% of the total net animals money/money income in the 
 sample (Seo and Mendelsohn, 2007). 
 All countries in the sample had a large number of animals 
 farms. Most of the farms in our survey were small household 
 farms, but a majority of the farms in South Africa and Kenya located in mild/not extreme climate zones were large commercial farms. 
 Definitions of what makes up a  small household farm against/compared to/or 
 a large commercial farm are country-specific. South Africa had 
 a large number of commercial beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  farms while Kenyan 
 farmers kept dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  and beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  in large numbers. Farmers in Egypt tended to raise chickens while West African farmers depended more on goats and sheep (Seo and Mendelsohn, 
 2007). 
 Climate data come from two sources: U.S. Defense Department satellites and weather station (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). We depended on 
 satellite temperature (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) and figured out (rain, snow, etc.) (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) from ground stations (see Mendelsohn et al. 
 [2007] for a described/explained explanation). The climate data measures 
 the long-run average weather (17 to 30 years), not the weather 
 in the particular year of the money-based survey. Climate data 
 were gathered in monthly measures of temperature (a--¦ C) and 
 (rain, snow, etc.) (mm/month) and then grouped by season: Winter (May, June, July), Spring (August, September, October), 
 Summer (November, December, January), and Fall (February, 
 March, April). Seasons for locations north of the equator were 
 defined in reverse. Soil data were gotten from the FAO digital soil map of the world (Food and Farming Organization 
 [FAO] 2004). Soil data were predicted to the district level 
 using GIS. The data set reports 116 most in control/most common soil types and 26 
 grouped soil types. 
 
