 Notes: (1) The base case is chickens. 
 (2) The critical value of chi-square statistic for the importance at 5% is 3.7. 
 (3) Three tests of worldwide  importance of the model: Chance ratio test: P &amp;lt; 0.0001, Lagrange multiplier test: P &amp;lt; 0.0001, and Wald test: P &amp;lt; 0.0001. 
 
 created the most animals income: beef (cows, bulls, etc.), dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), goats, sheep, and chickens. 5 We model the chance of 
 choosing each species as a function of summer and winter temperature and summer and winter (rain, snow, etc.). We also include 
 other explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) such as most in control/most common soils and a dummy 
 (number or thing that changes) for electricity. We identified the selection equations by 
 the input and output prices of the five species. For example, the 
 higher the price of milk (one of the first (or most important) outputs) the more 
 likely farmers are to choose dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  and goats, but the less 
 likely they are to choose sheep and beef (cows, bulls, etc.). 
 Table 1 shows the results of the multinomial logit moving backward 
 of the chance of choosing each of the five species. The base 
 case is a household that chose chickens. Most of the coefficient 
 guesses are very different from zero. The three tests 
 of the worldwide  importance of the model--chance ratio test, 
 Lagrange multiplier test, and Wald test--(check for truth/prove true) that the model 
 is highly significant. The coefficients report the odds ratio. For 
 example, the odds ratio of the electricity dummy for beef (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 is 2.6, which hints that farms with electricity are 2.6 times 
 (odds ratio) more likely to own beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  than farms without 
 electricity. Farms with electricity are also more likely to choose 
 sheep but less likely to choose dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  and goats. Soil (numbers that change/things that change) are weakly significant and their coefficients change/differ  across 
 animals species. For example, dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  are more likely to 
 be chosen under Cambisol soils, but not under Gleysol soils. 
 Under Gleysol soils, beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  are more likely to be selected, 
 compared with other species. 
 5 
 
 Species can be further (made different) by breeds (Oklahoma State University, 
 2007). For example, some breeds of beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  and sheep are more heat tolerant 
 than others. Information about breeds was not collected in the survey and so 
 this study does not tell the difference between different breeds within species. 
 
 Coefficients for animals prices are very different 
 from zero in most cases. As the price of milk, the first (or most important) output from dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  and goats, rises, more farmers choose dairy 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  and goats. Own animal price was hard to understand/explain because it is both the price of buying an animal (input price) and 
 the price of selling it (output price). In general, higher own 
 prices led farmers away from choosing a species. For example, 
 higher beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  prices discouraged farmers from selecting 
 beef (cows, bulls, etc.). Cross price effects are also obvious in Table 1. Negative cross price terms suggest that two animals are (can't work together) 
 whereas positive cross price terms suggest that they can be raised 
 both/together. For example, the coefficient on the price of goats (chickens) is positive (negative) for beef and dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  but negative 
 (positive) for sheep, suggesting that goats (chickens) can be raised 
 with (cows, bulls, etc.) (sheep) but not sheep (cattle). 
 Most climate (numbers that change/things that change) are very different from zero. 
 The quadratic summer temperature coefficients are positive for 
 goats, sheep, and dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  suggesting a U-shaped function 
 but the temperature response function for beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  is hillshaped. The quadratic coefficients of the (rain, snow, etc.) (numbers that change/things that change) 
 are usually positive, pointing to/showing a U shape except for beef (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 and dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  responses to winter (rain, snow, etc.). Although 
 not shown in Table 1, we also tested for the effects of other 
 important control (numbers that change/things that change) such as water availability, height, 
 and other social factors such as religion. These (numbers that change/things that change) were 
 dropped because they were not significant. We also tested a 
 number of (numbers that change/things that change) describing the farmer including (male/female status), 
 age, and education but these too were not significant and so 
 were dropped. 
 Fig. 2a graphs the relationship between the chance of 
 choosing a species and once-a-year temperature. Note that the mean 
 temperature in sub-Saharan Africa is 22a--¦ C. The chance of 
 
 S. N. Seo, R. Mendelsohn / Farming-based Money flow 38 (2008) 151-165 
 
 156 
 
 choosing beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  and dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  decreases quickly as temperature rises. In contrast, the chance of choosing goats and 
 sheep climbs as temperature rises. With chickens, the guessed 
 chance is hill-shaped, with a maximum at the current mean 
 temperature of Africa. The graph clearly shows/tells about that farmers 
 in Africa today choose animal species (in a way where only certain things are picked) to make the 
 best use of the current temperature. 
 Fig. 2b displays the guessed relationship between the chance of choosing a species and once-a-year (rain, snow, etc.). The 
 chance of choosing beef (cows, bulls, etc.), dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), and sheep all 
 decreases as (rain, snow, etc.) increases. Greater rainfall increases 
 the chance of sicknesses such as Trypanosomiasis (Nagana), 
 Theileriasis (East Coast Fever), and Crack (or argument) Valley Fever (Ford 
 and Katondo 1977; University of Georgia, 2007) and, maybe 
 more importantly, over a long time, shifts the community from 
 grassland to forest (Sankaran et al., 2005). All three of the large 
 grazing animals are clearly more productive in grasslands. In 
 contrast to the above results, goats and especially chickens are 
 more likely as rainfall increases. Goats may be (compared to other things) better 
 able to search successfully in forest settings. 
 In the second stage of the analysis, we guess the (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income functions. The net money/money income per animal for 
 each chosen species is moved backward on climate (numbers that change/things that change), soil (numbers that change/things that change), a dummy (number or thing that changes) for electricity, and sale price of the 
 corresponding animals. We identify these net money/money income (moving backwards) by the sale prices. We account for selection bias by using 
 the Dubin-McFadden selection bias correction terms. These 
 (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income (moving backwards) use the same seasonal climate (numbers that change/things that change) used in the choice (moving backwards). The functional 
 form is quadratic in both temperature and (rain, snow, etc.). 
 
 Table 2 summarizes the results of the moving backward of the (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income per animal. These (moving backwards) confirm that 
 the (may or may not happen, depending on something) net incomes from the five animals are sensitive to climate. For beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  and chickens, the linear terms 
 for summer temperature are positive and quadratic terms are 
 negative, suggesting a hill-shaped response function. For goats 
 and dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), the response functions are U-shaped, but the 
 coefficients of the second-order terms are not significant. Summer (rain, snow, etc.) response functions for all the species are Ushaped. Some soil (numbers that change/things that change) are significant. Gleysol soils are 
 especially harmful to dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), but helpful to sheep. The 
 price of dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), goats, chickens, and sheep have a positive 
 own price ability to stretch while the own price ability to stretch of beef (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 is unimportant. 
 The selection bias coefficients show/tell about interactions among the 
 species. If the coefficients are negative (positive), they suggest 
 that conditions which make the farm attractive to one species 
 would make it less (more) attractive to the other. For example, in 
 the beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  income moving backward, the coefficient on the selection 
 term for sheep is positive, but the selection term for chickens 
 is negative. The results show/tell about that farmers who the selection 
 model (described the future) would choose sheep (but who actually chose 
 beef cattle) have higher than people thought beef incomes. Whereas 
 if the selection model (described the future) the farmer would have chosen 
 chickens but the farmer actually chose beef (cows, bulls, etc.), that farmer 
 would have lower beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  income. 
