 species. The (may or may not happen, depending on something) net income per animal is generally 
 higher for beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  but it decreases quickly as temperature 
 rises until the temperature reaches the African mean temperature, at which point farmers stop choosing beef (cows, bulls, etc.) (see 
 Fig. 2a). Commercial beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  are very money-making but they 
 are mostly restricted to hardenate zones in Africa. Very differently, dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  net money/money income increases with higher temperature. Dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  operations are now mainly located in the 
 mild/not extreme zones in East Africa and Southern Africa, but they 
 are more widely spread across the continent than beef (cows, bulls, etc.). 
 The (may or may not happen, depending on something) net income per animal for goats, sheep, and 
 chickens changes with temperature, but the importance of the 
 change is (compared to other things) small compared to (cows, bulls, etc.). Ceteris paribus, 
 compared to beef (cows, bulls, etc.), these smaller animals--goats, sheep, 
 and chickens--are likely to become (compared to other things) more attractive 
 to African farmers as temperatures rise. The figure also points to/shows that dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  might substitute for beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  in higher 
 temperatures. 
 Fig. 3b shows how (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income responds to (rain, snow, etc.). It is important in understanding/explaining these results to recognize that increases in (rain, snow, etc.) in Africa suggest that land 
 moves/changes from grassland to forest (not from unproductive to more 
 productive (area of grassy land)land). The (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income of beef 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  decreases dangerously the wetter it gets, whereas dairy 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  net money/money income remain quite stable over a large range of (rain, snow, etc.). Sheep (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income also decreases with 
 (rain, snow, etc.). The (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income of goats and chickens increase (a) little. 
 We also guess a third set of (moving backwards) that (describe the future) the 
 number of animals chosen of each species. We identify this third 
 set of (moving backwards) by the percentage of grassland in each district. 
 
 159 
 
 Districts with more natural grassland can support more animals. 
 As reported in Table 3, farms in districts with more grassland 
 choose to own more beef (cows, bulls, etc.), dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), goats, and sheep per 
 household. Farms with electricity own more animals in general 
 but fewer sheep. Soil (numbers that change/things that change) are mostly unimportant, except 
 for the positive relationship between Gleysol soils and number 
 of sheep. Some of the selection bias correction terms are also 
 significant. 
 The number of each species of animals is defined to be a 
 quadratic function of summer and winter temperature and (rain, snow, etc.) as in the two previous (moving backwards). For each animal, 
 some of the climate (numbers that change/things that change) are significant (things that decide other things) of the 
 number of that species. Summer temperature is significant for 
 dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), chickens, and sheep, while winter temperature is 
 significant for goats and sheep. The number of goats and sheep 
 has a U-shaped relationship with winter temperature. Summer 
 (rain, snow, etc.) is significant for beef (cows, bulls, etc.), chickens, and sheep. 
 The response is U shaped for chickens, but hill shaped for beef 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  and sheep. 
 In Figs. 4a and b, we present how the guessed numbers of 
 animals change in response to hardenature and (rain, snow, etc.). 
 Fig. 4a shows that the number of beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  decreases sharply as 
 temperature increases while that of dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  shows a small/short 
 decrease. There are small increases in the numbers of goats 
 and sheep. Chickens have a U-shaped response function with 
 respect to both temperature and (rain, snow, etc.), but we leave out them 
 from both figures because they are at an (can't work together) scale. 
 Fig. 4b shows that the numbers of dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  and goats are 
 quite stable over a large range of (rain, snow, etc.), but the number 
 of beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  decreases quickly with more rainfall. The sheep 
 increase in number as rainfall increases, even though 
 
