 the change in temperature (described the future) by each climate model to 
 the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) temperature in each district. We also multiplied the 
 percentage change in (rain, snow, etc.) (described the future) by each climate 
 model by the (a measure of what occurs naturally/sports boundary line) (rain, snow, etc.) in each district or area of control/area of land. 
 This gave us a new climate for every district in Africa for each 
 model and each time period. 
 Table 5 summarizes the climate pictures/situations of the three models for the years 2020, 2060, and 2100. The models (describe the future) a 
 broad set of pictures/situations agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the range of results 
 in the latest IPCC (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate 
 Change) report (Houghton et al., 2001; IPCC, 2007). In 2100, 
 PCM (describes the future) a 2a--¦ C increase, CCSR (describes the future) a 4a--¦ C increase, and 
 CCC (describes the future) a 6a--¦ C increase in temperature in Africa. Rainfall 
 (statements about the future) are noisier: PCM (describes the future) an average 10% increase, 
 CCC (describes the future) a 10% decrease, while CCSR (describes the future) a 30% average decrease of rainfall in Africa. In addition to the mean rainfall in Africa changing/different (in a big way) across the pictures/situations, there is 
 also big difference/different version in rainfall across countries within each 
 picture/situation. 
 The three climate models (describe the future) temperatures to increase 
 steadily until 2100 although at different rates. (rain, snow, etc.) (statements about the future), however, change/differ  across time: CCC (describes the future) a declining 
 (popular thing/general way things are going); CCSR (describes the future) an initial decrease, and then increase, 
 and decrease again; PCM (describes the future) an initial increase, and then 
 decrease, and increase again. 
 We used the limits/guidelines from our guessed models in the 
