 We show the changes in the (may or may not happen, depending on something) net incomes per animal in Table 7. By 2100, the net income from beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  will 
 
 decrease over the next century by 30% with the PCM picture/situation, 
 by 10% according to the CCSR picture/situation, but increase by 50% 
 according to the CCC picture/situation. Net incomes for dairy (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 increase by 30-50% by the year 2100. Net incomes for sheep 
 increase with the CCC and CCSR pictures/situations, but decrease with 
 the PCM picture/situation. (opposite from what's expected), net incomes for goats increase according to CCSR and PCM pictures/situations, but decrease 
 with the CCC picture/situation. Net incomes for chickens increase especially under the wet PCM picture/situation in 2100. 
 Table 8 calculates the changes in the number of animals of 
 each species for each climate picture/situation. These results are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the previous two tables on chances and net 
 incomes pointing to/showing that beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  will (lower in number/get worse) (in a big way) 
 while goats, sheep, and chickens will increase over the coming 
 century. Across the models, the number of beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  is (described the future) to decrease by an average of 15 per farm in 2020, 20 per 
 farm in 2060, and 33 per farm in 2100. The number of dairy 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  is (described the future) to remain quite stable over the next 100 years. 
 Goats increase in number by 4 in 2020, by 7 in 2060, and by 13 
 on average in 2100. The numbers of sheep and chickens also 
 are expected to increase. 
 Combining the results from Tables 6, 7, and 8, the expected 
 change in net income is shown in Table 9 for each AOGCM 
 picture/situation. The current average income from animals management is around $900. For all the pictures/situations, the expected income 
 from animals farms is expected to drop (in a big way) by 2020, 
 by between 15 and 20%. In the CCC picture/situation, the loss from 
 animals part/area declines to 10% by 2060 and turns into a large 
 gain by 2100. With the CCSR picture/situation, the damages increase 
 to 25% in 2060 with more (rain, snow, etc.) but then shrink again 
 by 2100. With the PCM picture/situation, there is a 15% loss of income 
 by 2020, but this loss is offset completely by 2060, and turns 
 into a gain by 2100. 
 African farmers are expected to lose income at first because 
 they must switch away from beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  to animals that provide 
 lower returns (this way lowering the net income per animal) and 
 reducing the number of valuable animals. These net results 
 are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the usual Ricardian analysis of the 
 
