 The 95% confidence period of time (or space) was calculated for all of these 
 guesses using 200 help runs. The guessed damages 
 are very different from zero for most of the AOGCM 
 pictures/situations in 2020, 2060, and 2100 except for the PCM pictures/situations 
 in 2060 and 2100. 
 Table 9 also extends the analysis from the sample to all farms 
 in Africa. This leads to an guess of the group animals 
 hit/effect across Africa. The results suggest that the damage will 
 change/differ  from a loss of $9 to $12 billion in animals income in 
 2020, from zero to a $15 billion loss in 2060, and finally from 
 a loss of $5 billion to a gain of $100 billion in 2100. In the long 
 run, climate change will be helpful to the animals part/area in 
 Africa and this will offset some of the expected losses to crops 
 (Kurukulasuriya et al., 2006). 
 
 6. End/end result 
 This article uses a (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) equation model to take by force/take control of the 
 endogenous choices made by farmers and their resulting expected income. The model assumes that farmers choose the 
 profit-making the most of level of inputs for each animal, the species 
 that provides the highest net money/money income, and the number of animals of that species. The article tests whether these decisions 
 are influenced by climate. The resulting model gives ideas 
 into how farmers might change to fit climate change. 
 The model is applied to 5,000 animals farmers in Africa. 
 The multinomial choice model shows/tells about that the chance of 
 selecting beef (cows, bulls, etc.), dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), and chickens reduce sharply 
 in warmer places. This is completely agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) that commercial (cows, bulls, etc.)  operations are now located 
 only in mild/not extreme locations across Africa, such as South Africa 
 and Kenya. What's more, the model (describes the future) that numbers of 
 goats and sheep will increase with warming. This again is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) of where goats and sheep are now 
 located, in (compared to other things) hot locations such as Burkina Faso, Niger, 
 and Senegal. The model also shows/tells about that beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  and sheep 
 are more common in dryer areas, whereas goats and chickens 
 are more common in wetter locations. 
 The (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income analysis supports the multinomial choice results in general. Net money/money income of beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  is 
 lower in warmer places, but net money/money income of sheep is higher 
 in warmer places. In a wetter place, net money/money income from goats 
 and chickens is higher, but sheep net money/money income is lower. As a result, farmers move away from beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  to goats and 
 sheep in warmer places. Farmers move/change from (cows, bulls, etc.)  and sheep 
 to goats and chickens in wetter places and the reverse in dryer 
 places. 
 Finally, the (described the future) number of animals of each species 
 is also agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the results from the multinomial logit 
 choice and (may or may not happen, depending on something) net money/money income analysis. The number of 
 beef (cows, bulls, etc.)  declines quickly with warming while the number of 
 dairy (cows, bulls, etc.)  changes little. Very differently, the number of goats, 
 
 163 
 
 sheep, and chickens increases. With a (rain, snow, etc.) increase 
 (decrease), the number of<p><strong>NOTE: This document is incomplete. It was shortened to the maximum document length of 50,000 characters.</strong></p><div style="clear:both">&nbsp;</div>
